    "## Disease Background: \n",
    "*Fill in information and please note that this module is truncated and only has 5 bullets (instead of the 11 that you did for Module #1).*\n",
    "\n",
    "* Prevalence & incidence\n",
    "    - Pulmonary fibrosis (PF) is a chronic and progressive lung disease that leads to scarring (fibrosis) of the lung tissue. The global prevalence is estimated to be between 13–20 cases per 100,000 people, with higher rates in industrialized countries. In the United States, PF affects roughly 100,000–200,000 people, and about 30,000–40,000 new cases are diagnosed each year.\n",
    "    - The disease predominantly affects men over the age of 50, with the risk increasing significantly with age. Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis (IPF)—the most common and severe subtype—has an annual incidence of 10–20 cases per 100,000 individuals and a median survival rate of 3–5 years after diagnosis.\n",
    "    - Studies suggest that the incidence is rising, partly due to improved detection through high-resolution CT imaging and greater awareness of interstitial lung diseases.\n",
    "\n",
    "    https://respiratory-research.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12931-021-01791-z?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "* Risk factors (genetic, lifestyle)\n",
    "    - Genetic factors: Approximately 5–20% of pulmonary fibrosis cases are familial, indicating a strong hereditary component. Mutations in telomerase-related genes (TERT, TERC) shorten telomeres and impair cell repair, predisposing individuals to lung fibrosis. Additionally, mutations in surfactant protein genes (SFTPC, SFTPA2) disrupt alveolar stability and increase fibrosis risk. The MUC5B promoter variant is the most significant genetic risk factor identified to date—it increases the likelihood of developing IPF by several fold and may influence disease progression.\n",
    "    - Lifestyle and environmental factors: Prolonged cigarette smoking is the most consistent lifestyle risk factor and is linked to earlier disease onset and faster progression. Chronic exposure to occupational dusts and fibers (silica, asbestos, metal, and coal dust) also increases risk, as does exposure to environmental pollutants and toxic fumes. Certain medications, such as amiodarone, bleomycin, and methotrexate, can induce drug-related pulmonary fibrosis. Chronic viral infections (Epstein–Barr virus, hepatitis C, herpesviruses) and gastroesophageal reflux–related microaspiration have also been proposed as contributing factors.\n",
    "\n",
    "    https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/idiopathic-pulmonary-fibrosis/causes\n",
    "\n",
    "* Symptoms\n",
    "    - The early clinical presentation of pulmonary fibrosis is often insidious, making diagnosis challenging. The two hallmark symptoms are progressive exertional dyspnea (shortness of breath) and a persistent, dry, non-productive cough that worsens over time.\n",
    "    - As the disease advances, patients may develop fatigue, unexplained weight loss, and digital clubbing (widening of the fingertips). On physical examination, doctors may hear distinctive “Velcro-like” crackles at the lung bases during inspiration.\n",
    "    - n late stages, cyanosis (bluish skin tone) due to hypoxemia and swelling of the ankles and legs from pulmonary hypertension can occur. Recurrent respiratory infections are also common as lung function deteriorates.\n",
    "\n",
    "    https://www.pulmonaryfibrosis.org/understanding-pff/about-pulmonary-fibrosis/what-is-pulmonary-fibrosis?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n",
    "\n",
    "* Standard of care treatment(s)\n",
    "* Biological mechanisms (anatomy, organ physiology, cell & molecular physiology)"
