    "## Data-Set: \n",
    "*(Describe the data set(s) you will analyze. Cite the source(s) of the data. Describe how the data was collected -- What techniques were used? What units are the data measured in? Etc.)*\n",
    "\n",
    "The data set consists of images of mice lungs that were analyzed in my professor’s lab. These mice were experimentally induced with pulmonary fibrosis, and the images capture the resulting tissue changes. In the images, areas affected by the disease appear as white specks, while healthy lung tissue is represented in black.\n",
    "For our analysis, we selected all 78 images out of a total of 78 available pictures. The images were chosen to represent typical cases of disease distribution while avoiding extreme outliers, although one outlier was noted where white regions appeared around blood vessels. This is atypical, as pulmonary fibrosis generally manifests in lung tissue, and the white areas near vessels may reflect imaging artifacts or localized anomalies rather than true disease spread.\n",
    "The data was collected using imaging techniques in the lab, likely involving microscopy and staining methods to highlight fibrotic regions. Units of measurement are pixel-based for the images, with intensity representing disease presence (white = diseased, black = healthy). This subset of images allows for a detailed analysis of disease distribution and identification of patterns or anomalies in pulmonary fibrosis progression."
