    "## Conclusions and Ethical Implications: \n",
    "*(Think about the answer your analysis generated, draw conclusions related to your overarching question, and discuss the ethical implications of your conclusions.*\n",
    "\n",
    "From our analysis, we can conclude that pulmonary fibrosis does not affect lung tissue uniformly. The project data, which includes images from different depths, clearly shows that the extent of fibrosis—measured by the percentage of white pixels—varies depending on how deep the image was taken into the lung. By using interpolation, we can also conclude that there's a predictable relationship between depth and the amount of fibrotic tissue. This allows us to estimate the degree of fibrosis at depths where we didn't take an image, confirming that the disease follows a definable pattern of progression. Essentially, we've demonstrated that the spatial distribution of fibrosis is not random.\n",
    "\n",
    "The conclusion that pulmonary fibrosis develops unevenly across different depths of the lung carries important ethical implications. It reinforces the value of animal research in understanding complex diseases while also reminding us of the moral responsibility that comes with it. Although the study used only one mouse, inducing fibrosis still involves harm, so such work must always be justified by meaningful scientific outcomes and conducted under strict ethical oversight. I believe this research was carried out responsibly and in accordance with humane standards. Ethically, it is also important to interpret and present the findings with integrity—avoiding exaggeration of results and acknowledging limitations in scope. Finally, the conclusions highlight a duty to ensure that the knowledge gained from this study is used for beneficial purposes, such as improving treatment and prevention of pulmonary fibrosis, thereby giving purpose and value to the animal’s contribution to science. \n"
